import pandas as pd
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder, OrdinalEncoder

df = pd.read_csv("data.csv")
# One-Hot Encoding

df_onehot = pd.get_dummies(df, columns=['city'], drop_first=True)

# Label Encoding
le = LabelEncoder()
df['gender_label'] = le.fit_transform(df['gender'])

# Ordinal Encoding
ordinal = OrdinalEncoder(categories=[['Low', 'Medium', 'High']])
df['education_ordinal'] = ordinal.fit_transform(df[['education']])

# Frequency Encoding
freq_map = df['city'].value_counts(normalize=True)
df['city_freq'] = df['city'].map(freq_map)

# Target Encoding
target_mean = df.groupby('city')['salary'].mean()
df['city_target'] = df['city'].map(target_mean)

print("Categorical Encoding Completed")

#One-Hot Encoding
When to be used ;-
Nominal data (no order)

Algorithms like Linear Regression, Logistic Regression

How it works:
Creates binary columns for each category
#label encoding
When to be used;-
*Binary categories

*tree based models

How it works:
*Each category on the each unique integer
#Ordinal Encoding
When to be used;
Ordered categories (Low < Medium < High)

How it works
Assigns numbers based on logical order
#Ordinal Encoding
When to use:
Ordered categories (Low < Medium < High)

How it works:
*Assigns numbers based on logical order
#Ordinal Encoding
When to be use;-
Ordered categories (Low < Medium < High)

How it works;-
Assigns numbers based on logical order
#Target Encoding (Mean Encoding)
When to be used;-
Strong relationship between category & target

Common in Kaggle competitions

How it works;-
Replace category with mean of target variable for that category



